:"1136","1158":"1158","16 Feb 1991":"16 February 1991","1220":"1220","Abt 1136":"about 1136","1140":"1140","Kenemerton, Gloucestershire, England":"Kemerton, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom","of Aspull, Suffolk, England":"Aspull, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Richard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Rikert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]},{"name":"Rickert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Richard de Muscegros was born about 1136, in Kemerton, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom. He married Aubrey Albreda de Tregoz about 1161, in Aspull, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"Abt 1136–":"umbes 1136–Surnud","1140–Female":"1140–Surnud","1158–1220":"1158–1220","1136–Male":"1136–Surnud","14 Feb 1991":"14. veebruar 1991","Abt 1161":"umbes 1161","1136":"1136","1158":"1158","16 Feb 1991":"16. veebruar 1991","1220":"1220","Abt 1136":"umbes 1136","1140":"1140","Kenemerton, Gloucestershire, England":"Kemerton, Gloucestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","of Aspull, Suffolk, England":"Aspull, Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"Abt 1136–":"noin 1136–Kuollut","1140–Female":"1140–Kuollut","1158–1220":"1158–1220","1136–Male":"1136–Kuollut","14 Feb 1991":"14. helmikuuta 1991","Abt 1161":"noin 1161","1136":"1136","1158":"1158","16 Feb 1991":"16. helmikuuta 1991","1220":"1220","Abt 1136":"noin 1136","1140":"1140","Kenemerton, Gloucestershire, England":"Kemerton, Gloucestershire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","of Aspull, Suffolk, England":"Aspull, Lancashire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"Abt 1136–":"environ 1136–Décédé","1140–Female":"1140–Décédée","1158–1220":"1158–1220","1136–Male":"1136–Décédé","14 Feb 1991":"14 février 1991","Abt 1161":"environ 1161","1136":"1136","1158":"1158","16 Feb 1991":"16 février 1991","1220":"1220","Abt 1136":"environ 1136","1140":"1140","Kenemerton, Gloucestershire,